{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dd176a87-c090-4b85-9cc4-70a1a3076344","content":"Here are the issues I found in `.template.config/template.json`:\n\n**Error:**\n- **Line 9** – `\"datatype\": \"invalid-type\"` is not a valid datatype. Valid values are: `bool`, `choice`, `float`, `int`/`integer`, `hex`, `text`/`string`.\n\n**Warnings / Best practices:**\n- Missing `$schema` property (helps editors provide validation/IntelliSense).\n- Missing `identity` field (recommended for uniquely identifying the template).\n- `shortName` is `\"build\"` which could conflict with the built-in `dotnet build` command.\n\nThe critical issue is the invalid `datatype` value on line 9 — it will cause template engine errors at runtime. Replace it with a valid type, e.g. `\"string\"`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f0664222-3a7a-424a-b6d6-cce8d91a796c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me analyze this template.json file. This is a .NET template configuration file (used by `dotnet new`). Let me check for issues:\n\n1. **`$schema`** - Missing. It's a best practice to include the schema reference.\n2. **`identity`** - Missing. The `identity` field is recommended (though not strictly required in all versions).\n3. **`sourceName`** - Missing. Not required but commonly used.\n4. **`shortName`** - \"build\" - this is valid but could conflict with built-in commands.\n5. **`symbols.myParam.datatype`** - Set to `\"invalid-type\"`. The valid datatypes for a .NET template parameter are: `bool`, `choice`, `float`, `int`/`integer`, `hex`, `text`/`string`. `\"invalid-type\"` is not a valid datatype.\n\n\n6. The most critical issue is that `datatype` value—it needs to be changed to one of the recognized types like `text`, `choice`, `bool`, or `int`. The missing `$schema` and `identity` properties are best practices but not blocking errors.","outputTokens":504,"requestId":"93C9:2ADC27:9F9FD3:B9112F:69F2A7AE"},"id":"3da74d9b-199c-4f5a-aa2c-1bff178646a6","timestamp":"2026-04-30T0